{
  "text": "During cell life, membranes are submitted to an inhomogeneous and variable environment. Local inhomogeneities can be strongly related to biological processes, which has led to experiments investigating the effect of local modifications on biomimetic membranes [CITATION_1] . For instance, in the inner membrane of mitochondria, the enzymes that use the local pH difference across the membrane to synthesize adenosine triphosphate, the cell's fuel, are located in membrane invaginations called cristae [CITATION_2] . Experiments on model lipid membranes have shown that a local pH change can induce a local dynamical membrane deformation [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , and in particular the formation of cristae-like invaginations [CITATION_8] : membrane shape is tightly coupled to local pH inhomogeneities. Other concentration inhomogeneities in the environment of a cell have a crucial biological role, for instance in chemotaxis or in paracrine signaling. It is therefore of great interest to study the response of a biological membrane to a local modification of its environment.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "10292647",
